{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Since early modern times, the significance of hypothesis in natural science has been judged in widely different ways and has become the source of controversies.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "The purpose of this volume is to illuminate some general lines of development of those debates by treating cases from the history of science and philosophy.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Taken together; these cases show that the role hypothesis played and plays for natural science is of central importance for the manner in which science conceives of itself and its own methodology.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "The truth of general propositions a theory comprises can never be deduced from experience; the famous opposite opinions of Newton and Ampère notwithstanding.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "It seems to be impossible to identify the culprit for an error in the entangled net of experience and theory.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "The first one takes the hypotheticity of science as of highest significance.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "The conjectural character of scientific theories is taken as their hallmark.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "It follows that a true theory is impossible and that science must live with the perpetual susceptibility to error, and thus with permanent revision and a forever undecided truth-value.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "The second type of evaluating hypotheticity to be distinguished from the first takes hypotheticity for an important and inevitable mark of science as well.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Yet this type does not infer that we should renounce any claim to truth, but, on the contrary, to endorse it.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "According to this view, hypotheses can always come closer to the truth.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "The position of the third type does not doubt the fundamental hypotheticity of science either, but denies its relevance.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Science has not to be judged primarily according to its epistemic values but through its practical advantages.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Theories can be helpful in reaching this goal, but this is not necessarily so.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "The common origin is still present in the shared view that, in contrast to pre-modern conceptions from antiquity, hypothesis has a legitimate place and function in the process of knowledge.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "One can even say that rejecting this aspect of Aristotelian science and incorporating hypothetical elements into the presuppositions and methods of modern science is among the decisive hallmarks of the Scientific Revolution.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Instead of constituting irrefutable knowledge, science was increasingly seen as representing indemonstrable hypotheses.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Science's immutable certainty was more and more disputed and taken over by refutability as a criterion of science.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "Modern science's way of dealing with experience did not only imply the necessity of making room for hypotheses in science but also for limitations of scientific knowledge.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "To regard theories as hypotheses gives more possibilities in choice than if one remains wedded to traditional conception that identifies science with truth and truth-seeking.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
